[2026-07-04T16:10:00] TASK 3B — PIVOT (post-adversarial-review fix)
Coordinator relayed one real finding from logs/adversarial-generalist.build.log
("TASK 3B REVIEW"): `auth_callback` did two separate commits — one for
the `ZoteroConnection` insert (under the pre-rotation `session_id`), then
a second, separate commit inside `rotate_session`. A crash/error between
those two commits would leave the connection durably attached to the
un-rotated session_id, reopening exactly the session-fixation window
§9.1's rotation exists to close (narrow, previously untested, but real —
confirmed correct).
Fix: replaced the connection insert's own `db.commit()` with `db.flush()`
(visible to `rotate_session`'s own query within the same transaction,
not yet durable) and let `rotate_session` — which already migrates every
session-scoped row onto the new `session_id` and commits exactly once —
be the *only* commit in the handler. `rotate_session` (Task 1A's
function, unmodified) already queries `ZoteroConnection` rows by the old
`session_id` as part of its existing migration loop, so the just-flushed
connection is picked up and moved atomically along with everything else;
no changes needed to `rotate_session` itself. If anything raises before
that single commit (including inside `rotate_session`), `app.db.
get_session`'s `with Session(...) as session:` block rolls the whole
transaction back on exit, so the connection insert and the rotation now
either both happen or neither does.
Added `test_callback_failure_between_connection_insert_and_rotation_is_atomic`
— monkeypatches `app.routes.zotero.rotate_session` to raise after the
connection has been added (flushed) but before any commit, hits the
callback via a `TestClient(..., raise_server_exceptions=False)` to get a
500 instead of the test itself crashing, and asserts no `ZoteroConnection`
row exists at all afterward (not just "not under the old session_id") and
the pre-rotation `Session` row is untouched (rotation never completed).
Also added the two lower-priority route-layer tests the review flagged as
cheap-and-worth-it (previously only covered at Task 1C's module level):
`test_callback_returns_service_unavailable_when_zotero_is_unreachable`
(mocks a 503 from Zotero's access-token endpoint, asserts the callback
route maps `ZoteroOAuthProviderError` to CONTRACTS.md's `service_unavailable`
and that no connection row leaks through) and
`test_collections_returns_service_unavailable_when_stored_token_fails_to_decrypt`
(seeds a `ZoteroConnection` with a deliberately non-Fernet `oauth_token`,
asserts `decrypt_token`'s `ValueError` surfaces as a safe 503 at the
route layer, and that the raw garbage "ciphertext" never appears in the
response body).
Worked: `pytest -q` full backend suite => 177 passed (up from 142 at this
task's original COMPLETE entry — 3A/3C's concurrent work plus this fix's
3 new tests, no regressions); `pytest -q tests/test_zotero_routes.py`
alone => 14 passed (11 original + 3 new). `ruff check app/routes/zotero.py
tests/test_zotero_routes.py` => all checks passed. `mypy
app/routes/zotero.py` => success, no issues.
Changed: backend/app/routes/zotero.py (`auth_callback`'s commit sequence
— `db.commit()` -> `db.flush()` before `rotate_session`, plus an expanded
docstring explaining the atomicity guarantee); backend/tests/
test_zotero_routes.py (+3 tests: the atomicity/crash-simulation test and
the two service_unavailable/decrypt-failure route-layer tests).
