[2026-07-04T16:00:00] TASK 3D — PIVOT (blocking adversarial-review fix)
Adversarial review (logs/adversarial-generalist.build.log, "TASK 3D
REVIEW") found a BLOCKING issue overriding tester's prior "gate met"
verdict: the per-session inbound rate limiter was trivially bypassable.
`session_or_ip_key()` keyed strictly off `request.state.session.
session_id`, but `SessionIdentityMiddleware` (wired ahead of it) mints a
brand-new, free `Session` row/`session_id` for any cookie-less request —
so every request could get its own fresh bucket simply by not sending a
cookie. Reviewer proved this empirically: 30 requests via 30 fresh
cookie-less clients against a 10/minute-capped route all returned 200,
the limiter never engaging once. The per-IP fallback I'd written and
called out as a "backstop" in my COMPLETE entry was real code but dead
in the actual request path, since a session is always resolved by the
time the rate limiter runs in the real stack — it only executed in a
synthetic unit test that skipped session middleware entirely, which is
exactly why it survived two rounds of verification without being
exercised against the real vulnerability.

Fixed by redesigning the key hierarchy: **IP is now the primary,
unconditionally-enforced key** for every gated route (`_ip_key`, via
slowapi's `get_remote_address`) — checked first, always, regardless of
whether a session has been resolved. `session_id` is now a *secondary*,
additional, finer-grained check (`_session_key`, returns `None` rather
than falling back to anything when unresolved) layered on top — both
must pass. Each gated route in `_RATE_LIMITED_ROUTES` now carries an
`(session_limit, ip_limit)` pair rather than a single limit, with
`ip_limit` set to ~3x `session_limit` (e.g. search: 10/minute per
session, 30/minute per IP) — generous enough that a handful of genuinely
distinct legitimate sessions sharing one IP (office/campus NAT) aren't
punished, while still giving the IP dimension real, unconditional
teeth against the exact attack reviewer found. `InboundRateLimitMiddleware`
now checks the IP bucket first (reject immediately if over) and only then
the session bucket (if a session was actually resolved).

Rewrote `tests/test_middleware_ratelimit.py`'s scenario tests to match:
removed the old `test_two_distinct_sessions_each_get_their_own_budget`
premise (now literally false by design — two sessions sharing an IP
*do* interact via the shared IP bucket) in favor of
`test_two_distinct_persistent_sessions_sharing_an_ip_each_get_a_session_
budget` (proves the session dimension still gives real per-session
granularity as long as the combined total stays under the IP ceiling),
and added `test_ip_cap_engages_even_when_every_request_uses_a_fresh_
session_and_no_cookie` — the literal reproduction of reviewer's attack
(31 requests, each from a brand-new `TestClient`/cookie jar so
`SessionIdentityMiddleware` mints a fresh `session_id` every single
time, all from the same fixed test-client source IP) — asserting request
#31 now correctly gets 429, replacing the old dead-end
`test_ip_fallback_key_used_when_no_session_resolved` unit test that
never exercised the real request path.

Also addressed the SIGNIFICANT (non-blocking) item from the same review
round: `errors.py`'s docstring claimed "any unhandled exception,
regardless of type" gets the safe shape — true for ordinary responses,
but not achievable for a `StreamingResponse` (`GET /export.csv`) that
fails partway through, since the 200 status/some body bytes are already
flushed by the time a mid-stream exception occurs and there's no
response left to retroactively reshape into a 500. Corrected the
docstring to state this as a known, accepted limitation rather than
silently leaving the overbroad claim in place, and added a defensive
`try/except` + `logger.exception` around `export.py`'s row-streaming
loop (`_iter_saved_papers_csv`) so a mid-stream failure is at least loud
in server-side logs (monitoring can catch it) rather than silently
reading as an unusually short but otherwise normal export — re-raises
after logging, so client-visible behavior (a truncated file, no way to
signal an error in an already-started stream) is unchanged, only
observability improved. This touches `app/routes/export.py`, owned by
Task 3C, but done directly per the coordinator's explicit instruction in
this round and scoped to a minimal, additive logging wrapper — no
change to 3C's actual CSV-generation/neutralization logic.

Worked: full suite re-run — 212/212 passing (211 prior, net +1 after
removing 1 dead-path test and adding 2 new ones), `ruff check` clean,
`mypy --strict` clean. The new
`test_ip_cap_engages_even_when_every_request_uses_a_fresh_session_and_
no_cookie` test directly disproves reviewer's reported bypass against
